This study verifies the boundary equation of a charged droplet using various methods, and extends the Crowdy map for the 90$\degree$ contact angle droplet case to derive the complex potential of a droplet on a conducting plate.\\

\noindent For the 0$\degree$ contact angle droplet case, it constructs and examines the validity of a method linking  the local properties of droplets to their global geometry, involving, first, designing a specific charge distribution model to capture physical characteristics in specified scenarios, and second, applying an appropriate conformal mapping method to project geometric similarities in distant configurations.\\

\noindent By omitting the formulating of complicated droplet shapes, this approach simplifies the problem to a sufficiently accurate scale, providing tractable and generalizable droplet curve solutions. However, the study also argues that the global complex potential function fails to accurately capture the local contact angle due to the limitations in the current mapping function.\\

\noindent The mathematical methods employed in this study enrich current research on the phenomenon, introduce new insights into the fluid dynamics around charged droplets, and support the analysis of electrowetting under more general conditions.


